== Meaning of Pandera and Lack of Hebrew/Aramaic Original Text Quotations ==

I am curious if the Editors have read the original texts quoted in the Talmud?  I'm sure I could grab a copy, but that the Aramaic is not present in the article seems to be a glaring omission.  Afterall, a translation is already an intepretation.  Also, if Pandera is spelled פנדרה/פנדרא or similar, perhaps its a suggestion to Pandora?  Its uncommon for someone to be referred to as son/daughter or a female, but here the meaning would be loaded... if there is any basis for that interpretation... [[User:LFevas|LFevas]] ([[User talk:LFevas|talk]]) 22:08, 12 January 2012 (UTC)
:: Relating Pandera to Pandora requires a showing that the people referring to Pandera have a familiarity with Greek mythology.  Greek was prohibited reading among Jews for some time, which Talmud records.  It would require a showing why people concerned with Jewish law, history and culture would bother to refer to a particular character from Greek mythology.
[[Special:Contributions/4.248.222.74|4.248.222.74]] ([[User talk:4.248.222.74|talk]]) 14:02, 19 January 2012 (UTC)

